Description of the workshop - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
The Web has been identified as the most desirable platform for the access to distributed collaborative applications . However , the core Web does not provide enough support for the design and operation of distributed applications . Currently , numerous environments are striving to establish themselves as the platform of choice for distributed applications on the Web - examples include Netscape ONE , Microsofts ActiveX , Suns Java RMI and JOE , and many more research projects .
Each of these platforms has specific characteristics along several dimensions . Among these are support for mobility of objects and agents , secure communications , support for coordination , integration with standard Web environments , and support for personalized access to applications . Research projects tend to explore concepts along one of those dimensions in depth , whereas commercial products aim at a broad support of all of these features .
With respect to these dimensions , applications for Web based object- and agent-systems have diverse requirements . Applications in electronic commerce , for instance , require strong support for security , whereas applications in teleworking , telelearning , virtual conferencing , or software engineering put more emphasis on different coordination styles , mobility , or integration with standard Web technology .
The goal of this workshop is to asses the adequacy of object- and agent- technology to the requirements of different Web based applications . In order to do so , the current state-of-the art in object- and agent-systems for the Web shall be explored and the requirements of applications shall be examined . As a result , the workshop shall provide answers about the relation of current directions of technological development to the anticipated application domains .
Thus , papers presented at the workshop shall contribute to the following questions which will serve as a coarse structure of the sessions :
1 . Technology for Web agents and objects What is the current state of the art in technology for Web agents and objects , including research directions . Issues of interest are : o Coordination mechanisms for Web agents o Techniques for mobile Web agents o Handling of continuous data up to real-time o Wrapping of legacy applications o Security in Web agent systems o Scalability and efficiency of Web agent systems o Techniques for personalization and adaptivity of user controlled agents o How the environment for Web agent systems is integrated to standard Web technology 2 . Applications for Web agents What real applications does Web agent technology support today ? Experience reports and case-study are especially welcome from the following application domains : o Electronic commerce o Workflow management o Virtual conferencing and discussion support 3 . Adequacy of agent techniques for Web applications Web agent systems have a variety of interesting technical aspects . But are these functionalities adequate to the needs of applications and users ? Based on the presentation in the first two sessions , the workshop shall find out more on the following questions : o How is the design , implementation , and functionality of applications affected by technology offered by Web agent systems ? o What technology is required by applications , but not offered by current technology ?
Each session will begin with the presentation ( 15 min ) of a paper , up to four presentations per session , and a discussion amongst the participants up to one hour .
The goal of the workshop is to give answers to the above questions . The sessions and the discussions will be documented by the organizers .
Submitting papers - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
Papers submitted for the workshop should not be less than five , and no more than 15 pages in length . All papers will be reviewed for quality and relevance to the workshop .
Submission should be in electronic form only . Acceptable formats are Postscript ( if standard ) , or HTML . Please mail your submission to tolk @ cs . tu-berlin . de .
